 WORMHOLE n. A location in a monitor which contains the address of a routine,
with the specific intent of making it easy to substitute a different routine.
The follow- ing quote comes from "Polymorphic Systems," vol. 2, p. 54: "Any
type of I/O device can be substituted for the stan- dard device by loading a
simple driver routine for that device and installing its address in one of
the monitor's __________ *The term has been used to describe a hypothetical
astronomical situation where a black hole connects to the of the universe.
When this happens, information can pass through the wormhole, in only one
direction, much as pass down the monitor's wormholes."